g.text: Garte, the Cafeteria Manager: (His voice echoes from downstairs.) "What's going on up there?"
You: "This door will fall prostrate before The Law!" (Punch the door again.)
Pain Threshold: Nice try. The tears come streaming down your face as you crumble to the ground.
Pain Threshold: The tears bring some relief, but not much.
Kim Kitsuragi: He nods toward the staircase. "Come on, let's go down."
Composure: You've got this. Men like you don't cry unless it serves their purposes.
Kim Kitsuragi: "It must be an electronic lock. You will have to get Garte, the cafeteria manager, to open it first -- after you've paid for the night."
Kim Kitsuragi: "Our investigation does not at present require for anyone to go undercover. Let's drop this discussion and go settle your debt with the manager."
Kim Kitsuragi: The lieutenant looks at you with a mixture of pity and weariness. "Come on, let's go down."
Kim Kitsuragi: "Just a moment. We should talk about our progress on the investigation. Let's go out to the balcony."
Door, Room #1: Your key no longer turns in the lock.
Half Light: Just punch the damned door. No *locks* are going to keep you out.
You: "Right, I should go pay my debts before I can go to sleep."
Garte, the Cafeteria Manager: (His voice echoes from downstairs.) "What the hell is going on up there?"
Savoir Faire: You could try climbing into that trash bin in the yard, hobocop style... after you've gotten open the lid.
Garte, the Cafeteria Manager: (His voice echoes from downstairs.) "What's going on up there?"
You: Try to unlock the door.
Kim Kitsuragi: He nods. "Yes, we both need to get proper rest tonight."
You: "Actually, I don't need to pay -- I will brave the streets. Go undercover as a hobocop."
Kim Kitsuragi: "I would advise against that. It's already late, and you won't find cheaper accommodation in the vicinity."
Authority: He's asserting his leadership talents because he is concerned about you.
Pain Threshold: Your angry voice carries through the Whirling, but you still can't stop the tears from welling up in your eyes...
Physical Instrument: Pow-pow! That was impressive.
Kim Kitsuragi: The lieutenant purses his lips. "Admirable form. Now come on, let's go down."
Door, Room #1: The door rings from the impact, but does not budge.
Tutorial Agent: The door to your room locks every night at 21.00 if you haven't paid for the room. You can pay downstairs when speaking to Garte, the cafeteria manager.
Kim Kitsuragi: The lieutenant looks at you with a mixture of pity and weariness. "Come on, let's go down."
You: "Nah, I'll get by somehow. Didn't like that room very much anyway."
Door, Room #1: This is the door to your room.
This is the door to the room you *redecorated*.
Door, Room #1: The door appears undamaged, and even more impassive than the lieutenant.
Door, Room #1: The door shudders, but appears undamaged.
Savoir Faire: You could try climbing into that trash bin in the yard, hobocop style...
Savoir Faire: Hey, remember that trash bin idea...? Time to get climbing!
Volition: You feel uncertain, like a child who's lost his mother in the crowd.
Inland Empire: Because it's your last lifeline to being a police officer instead of a hobo.
Jump to: [Kim Kitsuragi: "The air outside is brisk, the lieut..."]
Kim Kitsuragi: The lieutenant looks on impassively. "Even if you could break down the door, all you would get is another bill."
Inland Empire: Yes, and it's not just a matter of comfort, but also of principle. This may be your last lifeline to being a police officer instead of a hobo.
You: Try one more time. This time with both fists, one after the other.
You: Observe the damage to your knuckles. Is this really worth it?
Kim Kitsuragi: "Just a moment. You had some questions earlier, I believe, and, besides, we should discuss our progress on the investigation. Let's go out to the balcony."
You: Still sounds better than sleeping outside.
Pain Threshold: It hurts, but keep your cool. You've got this.
Garte, the Cafeteria Manager: (His voice echoes from downstairs.) "What the hell is going on up there?"
You: Keep it in. Cradle your arm.
You: Confront the door with a stoical expression. You are still The Law.
You: Why would I want to stay in such a place?
Door, Room #1: Something about it has changed.
Physical Instrument: *Even if you could*? Don't let him talk you down, son!
Pain Threshold: Your fist bounces off the door and comes back to you on a wave of agony that surges up your arm.
